{{Politics of Ukraine}}
The '''2006 Parliamentary crisis in [[Ukraine]]''' started in March 2006 as a result of inconclusive [[Ukrainian parliamentary election, 2006|parliamentary elections]], and ended on 3 August 2006 with [[Viktor Yanukovych]] (as part of the [[Alliance of National Unity]]) being chosen as a [[Prime Minister of Ukraine|Prime Minister]] to replace [[Yuriy Yekhanurov]], who resigned right after the parliamentary elections.

Many speculated that [[Bloc Yulia Tymoshenko]] (BYuT) might form a coalition with [[Our Ukraine (political party)|Our Ukraine]] party and the [[Socialist Party of Ukraine]] (SPU) to prevent the [[Party of Regions]] from gaining power.<ref name=pm2006/> [[Yulia Tymoshenko]] solicited to become Prime Minister.<ref name=pm2006>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/4848958.stm Ukraine leaders jostle for power], [[BBC News]] (27 March 2006)</ref> However, negotiations with Our Ukraine and SPU faced many difficulties as the various blocs scrapped over posts and engaged in counter-negotiations with other groupings.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/country_profiles/1107869.stm Timeline: Ukraine], [[BBC News]] (Page last updated at 26 October 2009)</ref> Apparently [[President of Ukraine|President]] [[Viktor Yushchenko]] did not want Tymoshenko to become [[Prime Minister of Ukraine|Prime Minister]].<ref name=NoTymo&Moroz!!!>[https://books.google.com/books?id=C8C3xuqd6aMC&pg=PA214&lpg=PA214&dq=How+Ukraine+became+a+market+economy+and+democracy+%22Yushchenko+did+not+want+Tymoshenko+as+prime+minister+again%22&source=bl&ots=ui4As88O33&sig=403m68VYBSON1LFEid_-_vEAwn4&hl=nl&sa=X&ei=v1IGT7OiKIPtOdeDpPwC&ved=0CB4Q6AEwAA#v=onepage&q&f=false How Ukraine Became a Market Economy and Democracy] by [[Anders Åslund]], [[Peterson Institute for International Economics]], 2009, {{ISBN|0-88132-427-2}} (page 214)</ref> Initially SPU's [[Oleksandr Moroz]] wanted the post of [[Chairman of the Verkhovna Rada]].<ref name=NoTymo&Moroz!!!/>

On Wednesday 21 June 2006, the Ukrainian media reported that the three parties had finally reached a coalition agreement, which appeared to have ended nearly three months of political uncertainty.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/5101380.stm Ukraine allies 'agree coalition'], [[BBC News]] (21 June 2006)</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/5105192.stm Ukraine coalition deal confirmed], [[BBC News]] (22 June 2006)</ref>

Tymoshenko's nomination and confirmation as new Prime Minister was expected to be straightforward. However, the nomination was preconditioned on an election of her long-term rival [[Petro Poroshenko]] from Our Ukraine as the speaker of the parliament. Tymoshenko stated that she would vote for any speaker from the coalition.<ref name=Poro/> Within a few days after the coalition agreement had been signed, it became clear that the coalition members mistrusted each other,<ref name=Poro>{{uk icon}} [http://www.day.kiev.ua/164705/ Парламент почав працювати, але коаліції в ньому більше немає], День (7 July 2006)</ref> since they considered it to be a deviation from parliamentary procedures in order to hold a simultaneous vote on Poroshenko as the speaker and Tymoshenko as Prime Minister.<ref>[http://www.europeanforum.net/news/166/oleksandr_moroz_announced_a_new_coalition_for_ukraine Oleksandr Moroz announced a new coalition for Ukraine] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725235037/http://www.europeanforum.net/news/166/oleksandr_moroz_announced_a_new_coalition_for_ukraine |date=25 July 2011 }}, [[European Forum for Democracy and Solidarity]] (11 July 2006)</ref><ref>http://www.jamestown.org/single/?no_cache=1&tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D%3D31839 {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101226121532/http://www.jamestown.org/single/?no_cache=1&tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=31839 |date=26 December 2010 }}, [[Jamestown Foundation]] (4 July 2006)</ref>

The Party of Regions announced an ultimatum to the coalition, demanding that the parliamentary procedures be observed, asking membership in parliamentary committees to be allocated in proportion to seats held by each fraction, chairmanship in certain Parliamentary committees as well as Governorships in the [[Subdivisions of Ukraine|administrative subdivisions]] won by the Party of Regions.<ref name=PORL/><ref>[http://www.kyivpost.com/news/business/bus_general/detail/24728/ Ukrainian coalition, opposition to hold round table aimed to solve political crisis], [[Kyiv Post]] (3 July 2006)</ref> The Party of Regions complained the coalition agreement deprived the Party of Regions and the communists of any representation in the executive and leadership in parliamentary committees while in the local regional councils won by the Party of Regions, the coalition parties were locked out of all committees as well.<ref name=PORL>[http://www.rferl.org/content/article/1069496.html Opposition Blocks Ukrainian Parliament Session], [[Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty]] (27 June 2006 )</ref>

Members from the [[Party of Regions]] blocked the parliament from Thursday, 29 June<ref>
{{cite news|title=Sit-in disrupts Ukraine assembly|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/5127414.stm|work=BBC News|date=29 June 2006|accessdate=26 August 2006}}
</ref> through Thursday, 6 July.<ref>[http://www.ecoi.net/file_upload/1329_1200307242_ukraine-bulletin-100806.pdf ELECTION OF NEW PRIME MINISTER AND GOVERNMENT], [[European Country of Origin Information Network]] (August 2006)</ref>

Following a surprise nomination of Moroz as the Rada Chairman and his subsequent election late on 6 July with the support of the Party of Regions, the "Orange coalition" collapsed (Poroshenko had withdrawn his candidacy and had urged Moroz to do the same on 7 July<ref name=Poro/>).<ref>[http://www.kyivpost.com/news/business/bus_general/detail/24772/ Lawmakers loyal to Yushchenko call for new elections in Ukraine after pro-Russian parties announce coalition], [[Kyiv Post]] (11 July 2006)</ref><ref>[http://www.kyivpost.com/news/world/detail/24763/ Ukraine's Orange coalition falls apart after Socialists break ranks], [[Kyiv Post]] (7 July 2006)</ref> After the creation of a large coalition of majority (the so-called [[Alliance of National Unity]]), led by the former prime minister [[Viktor Yanukovych]] and composed of the [[Party of Regions]], [[Socialist Party of Ukraine|Socialists]] and [[Communist Party of Ukraine|Communists]], [[Viktor Yanukovych]] became Prime Minister.<ref>[http://www.kyivpost.com/news/nation/detail/24790/ Ukraine's political fate shifts amid Rada chaos], [[Kyiv Post]] (13 July 2006)</ref><ref>[http://www.rferl.org/content/article/1069700.html Ukraine's Leftists Announce New Coalition], [[Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty]] (7 July 2006 )</ref> Whilst Tymoshenko immediately announced that her political force would be in opposition to the new government,<ref name=BYUTOP>[http://archive.tymoshenko.com.ua/eng/exclusive/speeches-appeals/3352/ "We will be either in the opposition or we will fight in a new election"]{{dead link|date=September 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, Yulia Tymoshenko official website (7 July 2006)</ref> after the signing of the [[Universal of National Unity]] Our Ukraine initially wanted to join this coalition and indeed five of its members where appointed [[Cabinet of Ministers of Ukraine|Cabinet oMinisters]] in the coalition, but in October 2006 Our Ukraine joined the opposition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rferl.org/content/article/1071859.html|title=Ukraine: Two Viktors, But No Clear Winner|accessdate=6 October 2006 |work=[[Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty]]}}</ref><ref>[http://qa.rferl.org/content/article/1070421.html Analysis: The Faces Of Ukraine's New Cabinet], [[Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty]] (8 August 2006)</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2006/08/03/world/europe/03cnd-ukraine.html?ex=1157342400&en=f6fa44d44fcdec08&ei=5070 Ukrainian Leader Strikes Deal With Critics], ''[[The New York Times]]'', (3 August 2006)</ref><ref>[https://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F5091EFC3A5B0C778CDDA10894DE404482 Ukraine Leader Forms Alliance With Rivals], ''[[The New York Times]]'', (4 August 2006)</ref> By November 2006 there five ministers where dismissed by parliament or withdrawn by Our Ukraine.<ref>[http://www.unian.net/eng/news/news-171585.html Verkhovna Rada approves new Cabinet members], [[UNIAN]] (11 November 2006)</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=cQqr7f9QkngC&pg=PA106&dq=Our+Ukraine+Yanukovych&hl=nl&sa=X&ei=7CMGT9iGIM7sOYz2pbcB&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=Our%20Ukraine%20Yanukovych&f=false Ukraine on its meandering path between East and West] by [[Andrej Lushnycky]] and [[Mykola Riabchuk]], [[Peter Lang (publishing company)|Peter Lang]], 2009, {{ISBN|3-03911-607-X}} (page 38)</ref>

Following the [[2007 Ukrainian political crisis]] new elections were called and [[Ukrainian parliamentary election, 2007|held in 2007]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/6512941.stm|title=Ukrainian rivals rally in capital|date=1 April 2007|publisher=BBC News}}</ref>

